  number = {SP-638},
  address = {Naples, Italy},
  note = {Onboard computer systems (OBCS);Resource requirements;},
  abstract = {The availability of new high density FPGA technologies enables innovative
	approaches to the architecture of onboard computer systems (OBCS)
	for demanding small satellite applications. In the paper, we present
	the architecture of a highly integrated satellite computer exploiting
	the powerful features of Xilinx's Virtex-II Pro FPGA technology.
	The computing resources of the "Flying Laptop" satellite are provided
	by a single OBCS performing the control functions of a traditional
	satellite bus controller (SBC) as well as all tasks of the payload
	data handling and processing system (PDH). The unification of the
	different computing functions on board the satellite onto a single
	but highly redundant computer system results in clear-cut system
	structure and provides a high degree of fault tolerance with minimal
	resource requirements. he "Flying Laptop" micro satellite is under
	development at the Institute of Space Systems at the Universita&die;t
	Stuttgart. The primary mission objective is to demonstrate and qualify
	new small-satellite technologies for the future projects. In addition,
	the three main scientific payloads of the satellite will allow performing
	a number of ambitious earth observation experiments. According to
	the primary mission objectives, the OBCS itself will be a subject
	for evaluations of its innovative concepts and for qualification
	of its underlying hardware.},
